title: For Sale/Trade:  Zastava CZ999 Scorpion 9mm Pistol + 5 steel magazines
location: Uptown / Midtown / Downtown, Oklahoma City, Oklahoma
postcontent:
Made by Zastava. The CZ999 is an updated version of the CZ99 pistol. This was also imported as a railed version by Arsenal and EAA as the EZ9 or EZ99 pistol. (This pistol is not made by CZ, it just has CZ in the name.)

Milled steel slide with aluminum frame and fully chromed barrel. Has ambidextrous slide release, decocker and magazine release.

This gun is basically a cross between a Walther P88 and a Sig P226. It has the ergonomics and trigger similar to the Sig 226 in grip, size and weight. The single lever serves as both the slide lock / release and decocker and is ambidextrous on both sides. The magazine release button is also ambidextrous on both sides.

The trigger on this is very similar to Sig triggers. The double action is long and smooth with a very crisp single action. If I had to compare, I would say that Sigs have a slightly smoother and better double action, but the single action on this really nice and crisp. If you can shoot a Sig accurately, then you can shoot this just as accurate. This firearm is currently in service with the Serbian military and police.

I have about 50 rounds through the tube and it's been mainly a range toy for me. 

Asking $435 for this firearm and 5 steel magazine, plus the case it came in. I would entertain trades for a Gen 3 Glock 19 with 3-4 magazines.

title: For Sale:  WWII US ARMY Canvas External Frame "Mountain Backpack" 1943 Hinson MFC
postcontent:
This is a US Army field gear item. As issued during World War two. The backpacks that were employed by the US armed forces at the beginning of the war were less than adequate. The primary pack was the haversack , which was designed during WWI. it was cumbersome to use and did not hold enough cargo.

A new design was developed for the fighting men in the European mountains. Known as the "mountain backpack', the design consisted of a large main cargo area with three smaller pockets built to the front and sides. Of khaki canvas construction. The pack is supported by a metal frame. It has a large flap that secured the main cargo area. The inside of the flap has a smaller pocket where paper items, such as maps, could be secured. The flap is also where the black ink stamps are placed with the date of manufacture and the name of the company that produced it.

This backpack design was far superior than the haversack. It also inspired the development of the ALICE pack , which was used during the Vietnam war.

The main body of the US mountain backpack is attached to the metal frame by looping the straps at certain locations. The main means of securing the body comes from a leather section sewn to the top of the pack. The metal frame inserts into this section. A metal snap is then engaged to ensure the pack is held in place.

Ink stamping Hinson MFC. 1943 on inside flap. US stamp on outside flap. Has some small holes but otherwise not bad condition. Came from an estate from a gentleman that also had a lot of German captured items like bayonets and Mauser stocks. So chances are this pack was used in the European theater during WW2. Feel free to ask any questions you may have. Thank you!

 If you were to invest in something that would determine the outcome of the rest of your life, would you consult with just anyone?  Wouldn't you seek the knowledge of professionals in that particular field?  Your choice for Concealed Carry Legal Issue training is no different.   While many firearms owners have become skilled shooters, the truth is that a high degree of confusion remains as to when the use of deadly force is legally justifiable. With so many myths surrounding the subject and the complexity of the laws as they pertain to concealed carry, there is little wonder why both police officers and otherwise law-abiding citizens find themselves being prosecuted for actions they believed were both prudent and justified. postcontent:
Our # HG519379

Not since the classic Colt Ace service models has anyone accomplished the feat that this pistol embodied. The firearms market has been awash for the past few years with inferior Pot Metal 1911 copies, with names ranging from Chiappa to Walther stamped on them. Trouble is, you can’t stick a magnet to any part of those guns’s frames or slides. Here, at last, is a well, made credible conversion. Basic pistol is the tried and true Armscor Rock Island 1911A1 in the workhorse .45 ACP caliber; and it comes with an all steel complete slide assembly chambered in .22 Long Rifle caliber. Manufacturer is Armscor of the Philippines, a solid century old company. Importer is API of Nevada. Construction is entirely matte blue military type finish steel, with the exception of the pair of flat and rounded serrated surface polymer mainspring housing back strap pieces. Both slide assemblies are 5 inch barreled Government style. The .45 Slide is classic 1911 type, and the .22 LR slide assembly is a two piece open top device that supports a solid steel .695 diameter heavy barrel with dovetailed steel front sight and slide mounted low profile black combat rear sight. The .45 slide has dual dovetailed sights as well, white cowled barrel. Both slides have full length steel guide rods, although the .22’s rod has much less diameter than its .45 ACP mate. Trigger is .325 skeleton serrated face with overtravel adjustment, steel construction, and the photo specimen broke at a smooth, second-stage-feeling 4 pounds. Hammer is .300 skeleton Commander type, mated into a beavertail grip safety. Slide release and main safety are classid government type. Weight empty is just over 36 ounces in .22 configuration, and standard 38 ounces in .45 ACP. The .45 ACP Magazine is an Italian made blue steel ACT-Mag 8 rounder, and .22 LR magazine is polymer 10 rounder with steel guided spring. Replacement pricing on an Armscor 1911 paired with one of the pot metal .22 copies will destroy $800, and a person doesn’t really have anything with that pot metal add on. title: For Sale/Trade:  Assaulter's Sig P226 9mm+ SEAL issue Holsters & Mags
postcontent:
If you're looking for a pristine pretty little firearm to put in a safe, take pictures of to post in online forums and then finally shoot at some bullshit indoor range once a year then please, for the love of all things Holy, hit the back button now. This gun isn't for you.

If you're looking for a tried and true gunfighter's weapon, then, well, keep reading. This gun and the accessories that come with it, have seen some shit; real shit, in the real world. 

This is a West German marked Sig P226 9mm. It was made back in the day when Sigs were still Sigs. Are the Sigs that are being made now good? Yes, they're 'good'. I'd have no problem carrying a modern day Sig as a defensive weapon. They're fine. You know what they're not? They're not West German Sigs. Only a West German Sig is a real Sig. Sorry, I know someone will be butthurt about that but it's the truth. Also, those Sig "M25s" that Sig tries to tout as their Navy SEAL gun; well, that's a fine gun, but no, the tier 1 guys aren't carrying those. What are they carrying? This gun. They're carrying non-railed West German Sig P226 exactly like this one. 

This pistol served as a SWAT deputy's duty weapon right here in Florida. He was a former Navy SEAL and, after leaving the Navy and getting hired at the sheriff's office he decided he didn't want the Glocks they were issued and so instead he bought the exact same pistol he had been carrying for years in the Sandbox. Why?  He had a ton of USN issued German Sig mags (the ones you're getting here) and some holsters. 

Does it have holster wear? Yes. It has holster wear. If you're looking for showpiece then don't come see this gun. It was a duty weapon so it was well cared for but it was in and out of his holster as he worked the road in a busy part of the county. That's life; it's what happens to real guns in the hands of people who really use them and don't just collect them and talk shit on gun forums. 

This weapon has night sights and comes with the original (and fairly rare and sought after) Sig grips, as well as the more modern grips (the ones on the weapon in the picture). If you don't like the old style grips, you can easily sell them online for $75 all day long. 

Five of the six mags were US Navy issued mags issued to him in Virginia Beach, VA. These are the expensive and hard to find German zipperback mags. One of them is a Sig contracted Mec-Gar mag made in Italy. They are obviously all 15rd mags and I believe a few of them are LEO/MIL marked. The painted Safariland 6004 drop leg holster was also a USN issued piece of gear. It was "operator modified" to remove the upper legs strap, shorten the drop and added a retention strap which they placed around the pistol's grip when parachuting. The SERPA holster pictured is also a USN issued holster but was never worn in-theater so it's in perfect condition. Apparently all the guys used to use the Safariland 6004 and now, lately, they've all switched to the SERPA. You get both. The third holster, is his old duty holster for his sheriffs office patrol uniform. It is NOT a Navy SEAL issued holster. 

You'll get two cases with this pistol. The one pictured is the one the pistol came in. It is "Sig Law Enforcement" marked so it is somewhat collectable by Sig collectors... or so I am told. This gun originally came with 3 Mec-Gar mags (one of which is included) and the other two are nowhere to be found. The other case is a case for the Sig MK25 that I came into possession of. It is not the original case for this gun but, hey, it's a freebee. 

Anyway, this weapon is the real deal. You don't have to believe any of what I wrote above, but it's true. When we meet up and I explain my background you'll understand. You'd be getting a weapon with a hell of a lot of authentic history. He's a personal friend and when he switched from this full size Sig P226 to the slightly smaller P228 when he left patrol and became a detective he sold me this whole package. It's a great package but, to be honest, I'm just too much a striker fire fan so I have not been using this piece as much as it deserves because I love my Glocks. 

Anyway, if you buy this package you'll be all manly and women will love you and you'll look like a straight up operator and you'll shoot better and Hooters girls will flirt with you and actually mean it and strippers will give you their real names and your credit score will improve and you'll be better at home improvement projects and the pain in the ass kid with the loud stereo down the street will finally listen to you and slow the hell down and lower his music and all kinds of cool shit will happen to you. So buy it. Or trade me something cool for it.

I believe this sweetheart to be manufactured around 1992. She has seen few rounds...there is barely a cylinder rotation mark to be seen, the bore is perfect as is the cylinder and the timing. Rear sight is fully adjustable, vented rib and full underlug. Grips are original neoprene with the Colt emblem intact on both sides. A few faint marks in the finish only because it will scratch easily since it is high polished...some probably came that way from the factory...believe me when I say they are faint. To all of you serious collectors I am sure you own the polish cloth that will take these right off and make it look as new. I don't know what else I can say about this gem...she is just gorgeous!! This is one you should not miss out on if you are collecting...blue examples are must more plentiful than the high polished stainless.

title: For Sale:  Spikes Tactical Mid-lengthe 16" pre-ban upper
postcontent: This is a unfired factory assembled Spikes Tactical Mid- length 16" upper receiver.  I purchased this and never fired it. I decided to get a different upper and go a different route with my AR.   This does not include a bolt or charging handle, but I could add the original Spikes BCG and charging handle for $140.   This is not a pinned and welded upper, it has a flash suppressor and bayonet lug.   This is a great way to upgrade you "post ban " upper now that we can legally do so since we registered our assault weapons.  I know I hated my muzzle brake when I had it.   The mid length gas system is also far superior to the carbine length systems.   Less stress on the rifle , even less felt recoil, and more room to get a proper hand hold on the forearm.   Spikes uppers are chrome lined , m4 feed ramps, with 1 in 7 twist rate.  This is an excellent upper.
